    <name>
				<text>23.2.2.3 int sin nt & cos nt</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
Find the following integrals.
<ol class="HELM_parts_inline">
<li> \( \displaystyle{\int_{-\pi}^\pi }\sin nt \hspace{0.15cm}dt = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<p></p>
<li> \( \displaystyle{\int_{-\pi}^\pi } \cos nt \hspace{0.15cm} dt = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</li>
<p></p>
where \(n\) is an integer.</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[In fact both integrals are zero for
\[ \displaystyle{\int_{-\pi}^\pi }\sin nt \hspace{0.15cm}dt = \left[ -\dfrac{1}{n}\cos nt \right]_{-\pi}^\pi = \dfrac{1}{n}(-\cos n\pi + \cos n\pi ) = 0, \hspace{0.5cm} n \neq 0\]
\[ \displaystyle{\int_{-\pi}^\pi }\cos nt \hspace{0.15cm}dt = \left[ \dfrac{1}{n}\sin nt \right]_{-\pi}^\pi  = 0, \hspace{0.5cm} n \neq 0\]
As special cases, if \(n = 0\) the first integral is zero and the second integral has value \(2\pi\).]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
